April 7. and on the 7th of April, after a retreat marked with proofs of great alarm and precipitation, arrived in the neighbourhood of Wilmington. Soon after, general Greene, notwithſtanding his late defeat, endeavoured to make ſome vigorous attempts againſt the king's forces in South Carolina. As he had no means of providing for the wounded of his own, or the Britiſh forces, he wrote a letter to the neighbouring inhabitants of the Quaker perſuaſion; in which he mentioned that be had been brought up a Quaker, and urged them to take care of the wounded on both ſides. His recommendations
